content.text:
### MeshTransmissionMaterial Example in React Three Fiber

Source: https://context7.com/pmndrs/drei/llms.txt

Demonstrates the usage of MeshTransmissionMaterial for creating glass-like objects with advanced visual effects such as chromatic aberration, noise-based roughness blur, and improved transmission. It shows how to apply the material to different geometries and how to use a shared frame buffer object (FBO) for multiple transmissive objects to improve performance.

```jsx
import { Canvas } from '@react-three/fiber'
import {
  MeshTransmissionMaterial,
  Environment,
  OrbitControls,
  useFBO,
  PerspectiveCamera
} from '@react-three/drei'

function GlassSphere() {
  return (
    <mesh>
      <sphereGeometry args={[1, 64, 64]} />
      <MeshTransmissionMaterial
        transmission={1}
        thickness={0.5}
        roughness={0}
        chromaticAberration={0.03}
        anisotropicBlur={0.1}
        distortion={0.2}
        distortionScale={0.5}
        temporalDistortion={0.1}
        resolution={512}
        samples={16}
        backside
        backsideThickness={0.3}
      />
    </mesh>
  )
}

function FrostedGlass() {
  return (
    <mesh position={[3, 0, 0]}>
      <boxGeometry args={[2, 2, 0.1]} />
      <MeshTransmissionMaterial
        transmission={1}
        thickness={0.2}
        roughness={0.4}
        resolution={32} // Low res for performance with roughness
        chromaticAberration={0.02}
      />
    </mesh>
  )
}

// Shared buffer for multiple transmissive objects
function SharedBufferExample() {
  const buffer = useFBO()

  useFrame((state) => {
    state.gl.setRenderTarget(buffer)
    state.gl.render(state.scene, state.camera)
    state.gl.setRenderTarget(null)
  })

  return (
    <>
      <mesh position={[-1, 0, 0]}>
        <sphereGeometry />
        <MeshTransmissionMaterial buffer={buffer.texture} />
      </mesh>
      <mesh position={[1, 0, 0]}>
        <torusGeometry args={[0.5, 0.2, 16, 32]} />
        <MeshTransmissionMaterial buffer={buffer.texture} />
      </mesh>
    </>
  )
}

function App() {
  return (
    <Canvas>
      <GlassSphere />
      <FrostedGlass />

      {/* Objects visible through the glass */}
      <mesh position={[0, 0, -3]}>
        <boxGeometry />
        <meshStandardMaterial color="orange" />
      </mesh>

      <Environment preset="city" />
      <OrbitControls />
    </Canvas>
  )
}

```

--------------------------------

### Define MeshTransmissionMaterial Props in TypeScript

Source: https://github.com/pmndrs/drei/blob/master/docs/shaders/mesh-transmission-material.mdx

Defines the TypeScript type for MeshTransmissionMaterial properties, extending THREE.MeshPhysicalMaterial. It includes parameters for transmission, thickness, roughness, chromatic aberration, anisotropy, distortion, and buffer-related settings.

```tsx
type MeshTransmissionMaterialProps = ThreeElements['meshPhysicalMaterial'] & {
  /* Transmission, default: 1 */
  transmission?: number
  /* Thickness (refraction), default: 0 */
  thickness?: number
  /** Backside thickness (when backside is true), default: 0 */
  backsideThickness?: number
  /* Roughness (blur), default: 0 */
  roughness?: number
  /* Chromatic aberration, default: 0.03 */
  chromaticAberration?: number
  /* Anisotropy, default: 0.1 */
  anisotropicBlur?: number
  /* Distortion, default: 0 */
  distortion?: number
  /* Distortion scale, default: 0.5 */
  distortionScale?: number
  /* Temporal distortion (speed of movement), default: 0.0 */
  temporalDistortion?: number
  /** The scene rendered into a texture (use it to share a texture between materials), default: null  */
  buffer?: THREE.Texture
  /** transmissionSampler, you can use the threejs transmission sampler texture that is
   *  generated once for all transmissive materials. The upside is that it can be faster if you
   *  use multiple MeshPhysical and Transmission materials, the downside is that transmissive materials
   *  using this can't see other transparent or transmissive objects nor do you have control over the
   *  buffer and its resolution, default: false */
  transmissionSampler?: boolean
  /** Render the backside of the material (more cost, better results), default: false */
  backside?: boolean
  /** Resolution of the local buffer, default: undefined (fullscreen) */
  resolution?: number
  /** Resolution of the local buffer for backfaces, default: undefined (fullscreen) */
  backsideResolution?: number
  /** Refraction samples, default: 6 */
  samples?: number
  /** Buffer scene background (can be a texture, a cubetexture or a color), default: null */
  background?: THREE.Texture
}
```

### MeshTransmissionMaterial

Source: https://github.com/pmndrs/drei/blob/master/docs/shaders/mesh-transmission-material.mdx

MeshTransmissionMaterial is an enhanced version of THREE.MeshPhysicalMaterial. It offers similar functionality regarding transmission, thickness, index of refraction (ior), and roughness. Key improvements include support for chromatic aberration, noise-based roughness blur, and primitive anisotropic blur. A significant advantage over the original material is its ability to render other transmissive or transparent objects, leading to more realistic visual effects. However, it's important to note that this material can be performance-intensive because it requires an additional render pass of the scene. To mitigate performance impact, consider using lower sample counts and resolutions. For instance, when using roughness, a small resolution like 32x32 pixels can significantly improve performance while maintaining good visual quality.

--------------------------------

### MeshTransmissionMaterial

Source: https://github.com/pmndrs/drei/blob/master/docs/shaders/mesh-transmission-material.mdx

To optimize performance when multiple materials rendering the scene individually becomes too costly, you can share a buffer texture. One method is to enable `transmissionSampler`. This utilizes the internal buffer used by MeshPhysicalMaterials, which can be faster. The trade-off is that transmissive materials using this sampler will not be able to "see" other transparent or transmissive objects. Alternatively, you can manually provide a texture to the `buffer` prop, for example, by using `useFBO`. This gives you more control over the buffer and its resolution, allowing for custom rendering setups.

--------------------------------

### MeshTransmissionMaterial

Source: https://github.com/pmndrs/drei/blob/master/docs/shaders/mesh-transmission-material.mdx

By manually providing a buffer texture using `useFBO`, you can achieve a setup where multiple meshes share the same rendering buffer. This is useful for complex scenes where consistent reflections and refractions are desired across several objects. The example demonstrates how to create a buffer, render the scene into it, and then apply that buffer's texture to multiple `MeshTransmissionMaterial` instances. This approach allows for shared rendering resources, potentially improving performance and ensuring visual coherence.

### Initialize a React Three Fiber Scene with Canvas

Source: https://github.com/pmndrs/react-three-fiber/blob/master/docs/API/canvas.mdx

This snippet demonstrates the basic setup of a 3D scene using the Canvas component. It imports necessary modules and renders a simple scene with a point light and a mesh. This is the foundational step for any React Three Fiber application.

```jsx
import React from 'react'
import { Canvas } from '@react-three/fiber'

const App = () => (
  <Canvas>
    <pointLight position={[10, 10, 10]} />
    <mesh>
      <sphereGeometry />
      <meshStandardMaterial color="hotpink" />
    </mesh>
  </Canvas>
)
```

--------------------------------

### Setup React Three Fiber Canvas

Source: https://github.com/pmndrs/react-three-fiber/blob/master/docs/getting-started/your-first-scene.mdx

Initializes the React application and renders the Canvas component from '@react-three/fiber'. This component sets up the Three.js Scene and Camera automatically. The Canvas's size is determined by its parent container.

```jsx
import { createRoot } from 'react-dom/client'
import { Canvas } from '@react-three/fiber'

function App() {
  return (
    <div id="canvas-container">
      <Canvas />
    </div>
  )
}

createRoot(document.getElementById('root')).render(<App />)
```

--------------------------------

### Initialize 3D Scene with Canvas Component (React JSX)

Source: https://context7.com/pmndrs/react-three-fiber/llms.txt

The Canvas component is the entry point for creating a 3D scene. It sets up the Three.js scene, camera, renderer, and render loop. It accepts various props for configuration, including camera settings, shadow quality, device pixel ratio, WebGL context options, and event handlers.

```jsx
import { Canvas } from '@react-three/fiber'

function App() {
  return (
    <Canvas
      camera={{ position: [0, 0, 5], fov: 75 }}
      shadows
      dpr={[1, 2]}
      gl={{ antialias: true, alpha: true }}
      frameloop="always"
      onCreated={(state) => console.log('Canvas ready', state)}
      onPointerMissed={() => console.log('Clicked outside any mesh')}
    >
      <ambientLight intensity={0.5} />
      <pointLight position={[10, 10, 10]} />
      <mesh>
        <boxGeometry args={[1, 1, 1]} />
        <meshStandardMaterial color="orange" />
      </mesh>
    </Canvas>
  )
}
```

--------------------------------

### Performance Regression for Dynamic Quality Adjustment in React Three Fiber

Source: https://context7.com/pmndrs/react-three-fiber/llms.txt

The performance system enables dynamic quality adjustments based on user interaction, such as reducing resolution or effects during movement. This helps maintain a smooth user experience by prioritizing responsiveness.

```jsx
import { Canvas, useThree, useFrame } from '@react-three/fiber'
import { useEffect, useRef } from 'react'

function App() {
  return (
    <Canvas performance={{ min: 0.5, max: 1, debounce: 200 }}>
      <AdaptivePixelRatio />
      <Controls />
      <Scene />
    </Canvas>
  )
}

// Reduce quality during interaction
function Controls() {
  const regress = useThree((state) => state.performance.regress)
  const controlsRef = useRef()

  useEffect(() => {
    controlsRef.current?.addEventListener('change', regress)
    return () => controlsRef.current?.removeEventListener('change', regress)
  }, [regress])

  return <orbitControls ref={controlsRef} />
}

// Respond to performance changes
function AdaptivePixelRatio() {
  const current = useThree((state) => state.performance.current)
  const setDpr = useThree((state) => state.setDpr)

  useEffect(() => {
    // Scale pixel ratio based on performance factor (0.5 to 1)
    setDpr(window.devicePixelRatio * current)
  }, [current, setDpr])

  return null
}
```

### Your first scene > Setting up the Canvas

Source: https://github.com/pmndrs/react-three-fiber/blob/master/docs/getting-started/your-first-scene.mdx

The Canvas component does some important setup work behind the scenes:
- It sets up a **Scene** and a **Camera**, the basic building blocks necessary for rendering
- It renders our scene every frame, you do not need a traditional render-loop

Canvas is responsive to fit the parent node, so you can control how big it is by changing the parents width and height, in this case #canvas-container.

