## 8. Spline (spline.design) as an Alternative

### How It Works

Spline offers a visual 3D editor with React export. There are two integration paths:

1. **`@splinetool/react-spline`** -- Direct React component, loads a `.splinecode` file at runtime
2. **`@splinetool/r3f-spline`** -- Loads Spline scenes into react-three-fiber (gives you full R3F control)
3. **`@splinetool/loader`** -- Loads Spline objects into vanilla Three.js

### Bundle Size

| Package | Unpacked Size | Notes |
|---------|--------------|-------|
| `@splinetool/react-spline` | 26.8 KB | Thin wrapper |
| `@splinetool/runtime` | **6.82 MB** | The actual runtime (peer dependency) |

**Spline is NOT lighter than raw Three.js.** The runtime is approximately 6.82 MB unpacked (vs Three.js at ~1.23 MB). Spline bundles its own Three.js fork internally, so you would ship Two copies of Three.js if you use both.

### Verdict

Spline is excellent for designers who want to create 3D scenes visually, but for bundle size it is **significantly worse** than hand-coded R3F. Use Spline only if the design complexity justifies the 6+ MB runtime cost, and always lazy-load it.

