## 4. Glass Material -- MeshPhysicalMaterial (Native Three.js)

If you want to avoid the extra render pass cost of `MeshTransmissionMaterial`, you can use Three.js's built-in `MeshPhysicalMaterial`:

```tsx
function LightweightGlassSphere({ position, color }: {
  position: [number, number, number];
  color: string;
}) {
  return (
    <mesh position={position}>
      <sphereGeometry args={[0.5, 64, 64]} />
      <meshPhysicalMaterial
        transmission={1}
        thickness={0.5}
        roughness={0.05}
        ior={1.5}
        color={color}
        envMapIntensity={1}
        clearcoat={1}
        clearcoatRoughness={0}
      />
    </mesh>
  );
}
```

**MeshPhysicalMaterial vs MeshTransmissionMaterial:**

| Feature | MeshPhysicalMaterial | MeshTransmissionMaterial (drei) |
|---------|---------------------|-------------------------------|
| Chromatic aberration | No | Yes |
| Custom FBO resolution | No | Yes |
| Noise distortion | No | Yes |
| See other transparent objects through | No | Yes |
| Performance cost | 1x | 2-3x (extra render pass) |
| Bundle impact | Included in three.js | Adds drei dependency |

