### Approach 2: Pre-Rendered 3D Assets from Blender (Best Visual Quality)

**The idea**: Model paper pages in Blender with proper cloth physics, subsurface scattering for paper translucency, realistic lighting, and export as transparent PNGs.

**Workflow**:
1. Create a thin plane in Blender, apply cloth physics with high stiffness (paper, not fabric)
2. Use a noise texture for subtle surface irregularities
3. Apply subsurface scattering shader for paper's characteristic light diffusion
4. Render multiple views (3-5 paper pages at different angles) with transparent backgrounds (RGBA PNG)
5. Position in CSS with layered `filter: drop-shadow()` for runtime shadows
6. Animate with CSS transforms (the PNGs float)

**Key Blender settings** (from [Transparent Paper](https://transparent-paper.shop/blog/post/create-realistic-3d-paper-textures-in-blender/) and [Gachoki Studios](https://gachoki.com/how-to-render-transparent-png-images-in-blenders-cycles-and-eevee-render-engines/)):
- Render Properties > Film > Transparent checkbox
- Output Properties > File Format: PNG, Color: RGBA
- Material: Principled BSDF with Subsurface = 0.1, Roughness = 0.95
- Texture: Noise texture at very fine scale connected to Normal input for micro-fiber displacement

**Implementation in Next.js**:
```tsx
import Image from 'next/image';

function FloatingPaper({ src, style, className }: Props) {
  return (
    <motion.div className={`absolute ${className}`} style={style}>
      <Image
        src={src}
        alt=""
        width={250}
        height={350}
        priority
        className="drop-shadow-paper"
      />
    </motion.div>
  );
}
```

```css
.drop-shadow-paper {
  filter: drop-shadow(0 15px 30px rgba(0,0,0,0.18))
          drop-shadow(0 5px 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.08));
}
```

The `drop-shadow` filter follows the actual alpha contour of the PNG, so even curled corners and bent edges get shape-accurate shadows -- this is the killer advantage of the pre-rendered approach combined with `filter: drop-shadow()`.

**Evaluation**:
| Criterion | Score |
|-----------|-------|
| Visual quality | 9.5/10 -- photorealistic lighting, subsurface scattering, real paper fiber texture |
| Performance | 9/10 -- static images, no runtime computation; PNGs at 250px wide are ~30-80KB each with Next.js optimization |
| Implementation complexity | Medium -- requires Blender skill or stock assets, but CSS/React part is simple |
| Bundle size impact | ~100-250 KB for 3-5 paper PNGs (further reduced by Next.js `<Image>` WebP/AVIF) |
| Mobile support | Excellent -- just images with CSS transforms |

